metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #129
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Hyper Drive: B-Side #5
metadata.description:
Hyper Drive is based on the mathematics of recursion. Scale symmetry is used to create patterns that repeat at ever-smaller intervals, creating the illusion of infinite depth and complexity.

The rule for the recursive loop is incredibly simple. A box is drawn, then a snapshot of the full canvas is resized to cover the boundary. As this process is repeated, small variations in position create endless fractals.

This project is an experimental cross-chain collection, with a fully-generative A-side published via Art Blocks on Ethereum and an AI-based image composition B-side published via fxhash on Tezos. The artwork symbolizes the great divides we must cross, the connections we make along the way, and the disconnections we feel. We move through the world as the world moves through us.

metadata.name: Uniformed Cryptiloidz #2
metadata.description:

And they're here to hang out and literally bathe in everyone's attention.

They are courteous, witty, and prepared to astound you with intriguing and mysterious stories from the past and the future.

Layered using @Purespider's/fxhash-pfp code.

metadata.name: a pale reflection #301
metadata.description:
a canvas is prepared; grids and vignette applied.

marks are added (or not)

a drawing method is chosen

the drawing method is iterated, resulting in a heavily stippled image

the image is sent to a shader

various maths occur inside the shader

the resulting shaded image is then given a border

and thus to the screen

a pale reflection - original music here: https://rtsixty.bandcamp.com/track/pale-reflection 
listen while waiting to be signed.

metadata.name: Vacuole #23
metadata.description:
Vacuole emerged from a cellular automaton sketch to which I come back from time to time to experiment with different rules and mechanisms.

To celebrate #fxhashturnsone, I wanted to look for alternative forms than the classical top-to-bottom/bottow-to-top scanline growing behaviour. Vocuole instead uses a grid of fields, where each field is initialized with different rules, growing directions and settings. The system combines two different variations: classical elementary cellular automata rules and a copy-pixel/plasma rule, which takes pixels from the neighborhood with a noise-controled offset like a stamp.

metadata.name: Papercut Factory #68
metadata.description:
Folding and cutting papers was one of my favorite papercraft activities in my childhood. Even when I grew up, I continued to use papercutting as a fun activity with my nieces to cut even more interesting shapes and push the limits of our imaginations.

In Papercut Factory, I tried to translate those memories into code, and as a result, into generative art, by creating an almost infinite number of variations.

The use of different shapes, color and quality of paper, varying grids, cut zones, random cut shapes, sizes and positions, background style and color resulted in millions or even billions of possible unique outcomes.

I hope that you will find something beautiful from your childhood in Papercut Factory ðŸ¤—

metadata.name: Entrecroisement #142
metadata.description:
"Entrecroisement" is a French word meaning "intersections".
In this project, colored lines travel like rays of light that are reflected 
on the inner walls of a shape of a form in which it cannot exit. The different 
shapes are born (or filled) from these intersections.

The rendering time can take up to a minute
some parameters are adjustable with fx(params) and others are fixed according to the seeds 

To save a png file at 1500x2000 px type [s]

To render at 3000x4000 px resolution type [1] then press [s] 
type [2] to render at 4500x6000 px (can be long !)
---
100% done with p5js
some palettes comes from Werner's Nomenclature of Colors

metadata.name: Origin-a-tions III: Imagination #22
metadata.description:
The closer we look at things, the more different they will seem to us. The more we try to see what is, the more we will see what is not. Only our Imagination will fill the gap in-between.

Origin-a-tions is a three-parts series of generative artwork, started with Part I: Creation, continued with Part II: Formation, and concluded with Part III: Imagination, that depicts one possible variation of how things may be originating.

metadata.name: Up Above #129
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the feeling of insignificance. This feeling, which we all share and feel at some points in our lives is often referred to as negative. But I feel quite the contrary, this feeling is quite beautiful, as it shows small parts together can form something big.

We are but a speck in the universe, like a grain of sand on a beach, like a single drop of water in an ocean, like a single leaf on a tree. But together we are a forest, a river, a sea. Together we are the universe.

Feel free to explore this piece for as long as you want, and feel free to export it in any way you like, and use it for thing like prints, and, of course, I'd love to know about them :)

---

To export your iteration, click the menu bar at the bottom of the screen and press either the "Export current" or "Export custom" button.

metadata.name: Forgotten Memories #123
metadata.description:
Memories can be dark or they can be bright. Sometimes they are faint and pale, sometimes they are vivid and colorful. Sometimes they are hard to forget, sometimes they are easy to remember.

Memories are easily interrupted or even fractured, but they are also mostly always connected with other memories, whether they are related or not.

Forgotten Memories is what I consider to be my most ambitious study of color harmony yet. Each color represents a different category of memory, which are stored in our mind in layers of time. Their shapes differ in width and length depending on how weak/strong the memory was and how long it lasted.

Once a memory is forgotten, it may or may never be remembered again. But one thing that is not to be forgotten is that whether we choose to forget or remember, we are made of our memories.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #26
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.
